\begin_layout Standard
motivation.
 given a function 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 (taking and outputting real values) and a point 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}$
\end_inset

, we wish to expand 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x_{0}+h)=A+Bh+Ch^{2}+Dh^{3}+\dots$
\end_inset

.
 letting 
\begin_inset Formula $h=0$
\end_inset

, we see 
\begin_inset Formula $A=f(x_{0})$
\end_inset

.
 what about the higher coefficients? suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $h=10^{-9}$
\end_inset

 is a very small number.
 then 
\begin_inset Formula $h^{2}=10^{-18}$
\end_inset

 is even smaller, considerably so, not to mention the higher powers 
\begin_inset Formula $h^{3},h^{4},\dots$
\end_inset

.
 thus 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x_{0}+h)\sim f(x_{0})+Bh$
\end_inset

 is a linear approximation of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}$
\end_inset

, valid for very small 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

.
 so 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 is the slope, namely the rate of change of 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x_{0}+h)$
\end_inset

 with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

.
 this crucial coefficient 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 is called the derivative of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}$
\end_inset

, denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $f'(x_{0})$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $ $
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
example.
 if 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)=x^{2}$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x_{0}+h)=x_{0}^{2}+2x_{0}h+h^{2}$
\end_inset

, meaning 
\begin_inset Formula $f'(x_{0})=2x_{0}$
\end_inset

 for any 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}$
\end_inset

, or simply 
\begin_inset Formula $f'(x)=2x$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

